      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Why such a large difference?\n\nThis is a textbook illustration of the **chelate effect**. Both NH₃ and en donate nitrogen lone pairs to Ni²⁺, so the intrinsic metal–nitrogen bond strength is similar. However, en is a *bidentate* ligand: it forms a **five-membered chelate ring** upon binding, which provides a large **entropic advantage** — one en molecule displaces two NH₃ molecules, releasing two solvent/ligand molecules and increasing the disorder of the system. The thermodynamic data in SRD-46 confirm this: ΔH for Ni²⁺–en is ≈ 0 kJ/mol at 25 °C, while ΔS = +9.2 J/mol·K, meaning the binding is **entropy-driven** — a hallmark of chelation.\n\n> **Source:** NIST SRD-46 (vlm_173185 for NH₃; vlm_122371 for en), both at 25 °C, I = 0 M (aqueous).",
